description:
I've been trying to use Pitivi for the last 10 years. Seriously. I was 18 and I wanted to assemble footage of my shiny new Panasonic camera. Back in the days the closed format of the generated video files was the big issue. Even with the relevant codecs installed Pitivi would inevitably crash and layering was a distant dream (even though it was 2008, not the 80s).

Fast-forward 10 years and my videos (same format, higher resolution at best) import correctly! That's good news; unfortunately Pitivi is still appallingly slow, buggy and unpredictable. 

- the proxy assets (downscaled version to make the editing faster) never finished being generated and the size on disk was about 1.4G when I decided to kill the process. My original file is about 200Mo;
- muting the audio of a video requires finding the right audio effect in the library and turning down its volume property;
- transitions are incredibly buggy and slow;
- no ability to toggle hide/show on a clip (to see where the underlying clip is for example).

I could probably add a lot more if I didn't abandon Pitivi in despair everytime I try and edit the simplest things. Developers: either use the software (and eat your own dog food) or find another project to hack away because Pitivi never worked, probably never will, and deserve to be buried respectfully. From its ashes a new editor can rise and finally offer a coherent offer for a beautiful GTK+, GStreamer, GNOME-style video editor.
